%I A396886 #5 Jun 09 2026 08:42:40
%S A396886 1,1,1,4,47,2951,1317746,2838399010
%N A396886 Number of unlabeled minimally 7-rigid graphs on n vertices.
%C A396886 A graph G is d-rigid, if every generic realization p in dimension d yields a framework (G,p) that is infinitesimally d-rigid; i.e., all its infinitesimal flexes are trivial. It is minimally d-rigid if it is d-rigid but looses this property upon deletion of any edge.
%C A396886 Every minimally 7-rigid graph with n>7 is (7,28)-sparse, that is every subgraph with n'>=7 vertices spans at most 7n'-28 edges. Minimally 7-rigid graphs have 7n-28 edges and hence are (7,28)-tight but not every (7,28)-tight graph is minimally 7-rigid.
%H A396886 Matteo Gallet, Georg Grasegger, Matthias Himmelmann and Jan Legerský, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3815171">PyRigi -- a general-purpose Python package for the rigidity and flexibility of bar-and-joint frameworks</a>, ACM Transactions on Mathematical Software, 2026.
%H A396886 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18548603">Dataset of minimally d-rigid graphs</a>, 2026.
%H A396886 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7457820">RigiComp - A Mathematica package for computational rigidity of graphs</a>, 2022.
%H A396886 PyRigi Developers, <a href="https://pyrigi.github.io/PyRigi/math/rigidity.html">Rigidity Theory</a>, 2025.
%H A396886 Walter Whiteley, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/conm/197">Some matroids from discrete applied geometry</a>, 1996.
%e A396886 The complete graphs on seven and eight vertices are minimally 7-rigid.
%e A396886 So is the complete graph on nine vertices with one edge removed. The three graphs that can be obtained from the previous one by adding a new vertex and connecting it to 7 of the existing vertices, are also minimally 7-rigid.
